data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Change

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised. Your `Stop()` method will crash and your catch block is dead code.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so GetNextItem can unblock on cancellation
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Graceful shutdown requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _cts.Cancel();

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait gracefully, then walk away (task will finish on its own)
            await Task.WhenAny(
                _workerTask,
                Task.Delay(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5))
            );
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | The #1 migration blocker. There is no equivalent — you **must** use cooperative cancellation. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` → also gone** | Dead code in .NET 8. Remove it. |
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()` ignores cancellation** | If the original blocks on a `Queue.Dequeue` or DB call, cancellation can't interrupt it. You must pass `CancellationToken` into the blocking call (e.g., `Channel.ReadAsync(token)`, `BlockingCollection.Take(token)`). |
| **`volatile bool` flag is insufficient** | A flag can't wake a thread blocked inside a syscall. `CancellationToken` integrates with async I/O and `WaitHandle`s to actually unblock. |
| **`Thread.Sleep(2000)` → `Task.Delay`** | `Thread.Sleep` blocks the calling thread. Use `await Task.Delay()` in async code. |
| **Fire-and-forget `Task.Run`** | Always store and await the `Task`. Unobserved exceptions silently vanish otherwise. |

### If You Can't Make Methods Async

When wrapping legacy sync code that you can't change yet:

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        try
        {
            // Poll the token alongside your blocking call
            var item = GetNextItem(token); // overload that accepts token
            token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
            ProcessItem(item);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
            break;
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

### Also Consider: `BackgroundService`

.NET 8's hosted services handle the lifecycle for you:

```csharp
public class MyProcessor : BackgroundService
{
    protected override async Task ExecuteAsync(CancellationToken stoppingToken)
    {
        while (!stoppingToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            var item = await GetNextItemAsync(stoppingToken);
            await ProcessItemAsync(item, stoppingToken);
        }
    }
}

// Registration in Program.cs:
builder.Services.AddHostedService<MyProcessor>();
```

This gives you automatic startup/shutdown, DI integration, and proper cancellation wired to app lifetime — no manual thread management at all.
